	abstract = {The Jiangmen Underground Neutrino Observatory ({JUNO}) is a 20 kton {LS} detector at 700-m underground. An excellent energy resolution and a large fiducial volume offer exciting opportunities for addressing many important topics in neutrino and astro-particle physics. With 6 years of data, the neutrino mass ordering can be determined at 3-4 sigma and three oscillation parameters can be measured to a precision of 0.6\% or better by detecting reactor antineutrinos. With 10 years of data, {DSNB} could be observed at 3-sigma; a lower limit of the proton lifetime of 8.34e33 years (90\% C.L.) can be set by searching for p-{\textgreater}nu\_bar K{\textasciicircum}+; detection of solar neutrinos would shed new light on the solar metallicity problem and examine the vacuum-matter transition region. A core-collapse supernova at 10 kpc would lead to {\textasciitilde}5000 {IBD} and {\textasciitilde}2000 (300) all-flavor neutrino-proton (electron) scattering events. Geo-neutrinos can be detected with a rate of {\textasciitilde}400 events/year. We also summarize the final design of the {JUNO} detector and the key R\&D achievements. All 20-inch {PMTs} have been tested. The average photon detection efficiency is 28.9\% for the 15,000 {MCP} {PMTs} and 28.1\% for the 5,000 dynode {PMTs}, higher than the {JUNO} requirement of 27\%. Together with the {\textgreater}20 m attenuation length of {LS}, we expect a yield of 1345 p.e. per {MeV} and an effective energy resolution of 3.02\%/{\textbackslash}sqrt\{E ({MeV})\}\$ in simulations. The underwater electronics is designed to have a loss rate {\textless}0.5\% in 6 years. With degassing membranes and a micro-bubble system, the radon concentration in the 35-kton water pool could be lowered to {\textless}10 {mBq}/m{\textasciicircum}3. Acrylic panels of radiopurity {\textless}0.5 ppt U/Th are produced. The 20-kton {LS} will be purified onsite. Singles in the fiducial volume can be controlled to {\textasciitilde}10 Hz. The {JUNO} e